    All of the classifications mentioned above also acknowledge the fact that not all definite descriptions depend on the previous discourse for their interpretation.
    Some refer to an entity in the physical environment, others to objects which are assumed to be known on the basis of common knowledge (Prince's &amp;quot;discourse-new/hearer-old&amp;quot; expressions, such as the pope), and still others are licensed by virtue of the semantics of their head noun and complement (as in the fact that Milan won the Italian football championship).
    In the experiments discussed in Poesio and Vieira (1998) we asked our subjects to classify all definite description uses in our two corpora.
